#: ../../../prompt.rst:2
msgid "Writing your own prompt"
msgstr "編寫你自己的提示"

#: ../../../prompt.rst:7
msgid ""
"This document uses formatting to show what a prompt would look like. If you "
"are viewing this in the man page, you probably want to switch to looking at "
"the html version instead. Run ``help custom-prompt`` to view it in a web "
"browser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:10
msgid ""
"Fish ships a number of prompts that you can view with the :doc:`fish_config "
"<cmds/fish_config>` command, and many users have shared their prompts online."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:12
msgid ""
"However, you can also write your own, or adjust an existing prompt. This is "
"a good way to get used to fish's :doc:`scripting language <language>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:14
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish's prompt is built by running a function - :doc:"
"`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>`. Or, more specifically, three functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:16
msgid ""
":doc:`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>`, which is the main prompt function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:17
msgid ""
":doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/fish_right_prompt>`, which is shown on the "
"right side of the terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:18
msgid ""
":doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/fish_mode_prompt>`, which is shown if :ref:`vi-"
"mode <vi-mode>` is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:20
msgid ""
"These functions are run, and whatever they print is displayed as the prompt "
"(minus one trailing newline)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:22
msgid "Here, we will just be writing a simple fish_prompt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:25
msgid "Our first prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:27
msgid "Let's look at a very simple example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:29
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    echo $PWD '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:33
msgid ""
"This prints the current working directory (:envvar:`PWD`) and a ``>`` symbol "
"to show where the prompt ends. The ``>`` is :ref:`quoted <quotes>` because "
"otherwise it would signify a :ref:`redirection <redirects>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:35
msgid ""
"Because we've used :doc:`echo <cmds/echo>`, it adds spaces between the two "
"so it ends up looking like (assuming ``_`` is your cursor):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:41
msgid ":white:`/home/tutorial >`\\ _"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:44
msgid "Formatting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:46
msgid ""
"``echo`` adds spaces between its arguments. If you don't want those, you can "
"use :doc:`string join <cmds/string-join>` like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:48
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- $PWD '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:52
msgid ""
"The ``--`` indicates to ``string`` that no options can come after it, in "
"case we extend this with something that can start with a ``-``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:54
msgid ""
"There are other ways to remove the space, including ``echo -s`` and :doc:"
"`printf <cmds/printf>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:57
msgid "Adding colo(u)r"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:59
msgid "This prompt is functional, but a bit boring. We could add some color."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:61
msgid ""
"Fortunately, fish offers the :doc:`set_color <cmds/set_color>` command, so "
"you can do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:63
msgid "echo (set_color red)foo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:65
msgid ""
"``set_color`` can also handle RGB colors like ``set_color 23b455``, and "
"other formatting options including bold and italics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:67
msgid "So, taking our previous prompt and adding some color::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:69
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) $PWD (set_color normal) '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:73
msgid ""
"A \"normal\" color tells the terminal to go back to its normal formatting "
"options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:75
msgid ""
"What ``set_color`` does internally is to print an escape sequence that tells "
"the terminal to change color. So if you see something like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:77
msgid "echo \\e\\[31mfoo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:79
msgid "that could just be ``set_color red``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:82
msgid "Shortening the working directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:84
msgid ""
"This is fine, but our :envvar:`PWD` can be a bit long, and we are typically "
"only interested in the last few directories. We can shorten this with the :"
"doc:`prompt_pwd <cmds/prompt_pwd>` helper that will give us a shortened "
"working directory::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:86
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd) (set_color normal) '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:90
msgid ""
"``prompt_pwd`` takes options to control how much to shorten. For instance, "
"if we want to display the last two directories, we'd use ``prompt_pwd --full-"
"length-dirs 2``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:92
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd --full-length-dirs 2) "
"(set_color normal) '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:96
msgid ""
"With a current directory of \"/home/tutorial/Music/Lena Raine/Oneknowing\", "
"this would print"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:102
msgid ":green:`~/M/Lena Raine/Oneknowing`>_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:105
msgid "Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:107
msgid ""
"One important bit of information that every command returns is the :ref:"
"`status <variables-status>`. This is a whole number from 0 to 255, and "
"usually it is used as an error code - 0 if the command returned "
"successfully, or a number from 1 to 255 if not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:109
msgid ""
"It's useful to display this in your prompt, but showing it when it's 0 seems "
"kind of wasteful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:111
msgid ""
"First of all, since every command (except for :doc:`set <cmds/set>`) changes "
"the status, you need to store it for later use as the first thing in your "
"prompt. Use a :ref:`local variable <variables-scope>` so it will be confined "
"to your prompt function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:113
msgid "set -l last_status $status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:115
msgid "And after that, you can set a string if it not zero::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:117
msgid ""
"# Prompt status only if it's not 0\n"
"set -l stat\n"
"if test $last_status -ne 0\n"
"    set stat (set_color red)\"[$last_status]\"(set_color normal)\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:123
msgid "And to print it, we add it to our ``string join``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:125
msgid ""
"string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd) (set_color normal) $stat '>'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:127
msgid ""
"If ``$last_status`` was 0, ``$stat`` is empty, and so it will simply "
"disappear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:129
msgid "So our entire prompt is now::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:131
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    set -l last_status $status\n"
"    # Prompt status only if it's not 0\n"
"    set -l stat\n"
"    if test $last_status -ne 0\n"
"        set stat (set_color red)\"[$last_status]\"(set_color normal)\n"
"    end\n"
"\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd) (set_color normal) "
"$stat '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:142
msgid "And it looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:149
msgid ":green:`~/M/L/Oneknowing`\\ :red:`[1]`>_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:151
msgid "after we run ``false`` (which returns 1)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:154
msgid "Where to go from here?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:156
msgid ""
"We have now built a simple but working and usable prompt, but of course more "
"can be done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:158
msgid ""
"Fish offers more helper functions: - ``prompt_login`` to describe the user/"
"hostname/container or ``prompt_hostname`` to describe just the host - "
"``fish_is_root_user`` to help with changing the symbol for root. - "
"``fish_vcs_prompt`` to show version control information (or "
"``fish_git_prompt`` / ``fish_hg_prompt`` / ``fish_svn_prompt`` to limit it "
"to specific systems)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:162
msgid ""
"You can add a right prompt by changing :doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/"
"fish_right_prompt>` or a vi-mode prompt by changing :doc:`fish_mode_prompt "
"<cmds/fish_mode_prompt>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:163
msgid ""
"Some prompts have interesting or advanced features - Add the time when the "
"prompt was printed - Show various integrations like python's venv - Color "
"the parts differently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:168
msgid ""
"You can look at fish's sample prompts for inspiration. Open up :doc:"
"`fish_config <cmds/fish_config>`, find one you like and pick it. For "
"example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:170
msgid ""
"fish_config prompt show # <- shows all the sample prompts\n"
"fish_config prompt choose disco # <- this picks the \"disco\" prompt for "
"this session\n"
"funced fish_prompt # <- opens fish_prompt in your editor, and reloads it "
"once the editor exits"
msgstr ""
